/3/level0.json"}]}}]}],"annotations":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-14143/canvas/1/page/p1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-14143/canvas/1/ece687e4-11ca-4736-98e2-99e54d0fdc3b","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-07-01T15:17:02.550Z","creator":"lucia","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>Alma’s background remains a mystery to viewers. It’s clear that she immigrated to England at some point, perhaps during the war as a Jewish refugee, but beyond that, her history is unexplored in the film, leaving her a bit of a blank canvas for Reynolds to project onto. Scenes involving Alma’s brother were ultimately cut from the film (Bell, “<a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" class=\"Hyperlink SCXW73900468 BCX2\" href=\"https://www.bfi.org.uk/sight-and-sound/features/paul-thomas-anderson-phantom-thread-1950s-london-haute-couture-gothic-romance-daniel-day-lewis-vicky-krieps\"><u>Paul Thomas Anderson on Phantom Thread</u></a>”).&nbsp;</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-14143/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:55.32467532467518,131.6883116883116,365.4545454545455,183.89610389610394"}}}]}]}]}